The paper discusses the disconnect between the algorithmic perspective of computer scientists and the statistical perspective of statisticians, scientific computers, and machine learners. It focuses on statistical regularization, which is central to nearly every application domain that applies algorithms to noisy data. The paper also discusses how approximate computation can implicitly lead to statistical regularization. Based on these topics, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.DB (Databases), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of algorithms for noisy data, which suggests the sub-categories cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IT (Information Theory) as possible categories as well.
